\section{The lineage ID}{


Every row in every tagged dataset carries a \code{lineage_id} column. For
datasets with a \code{USUBJID} column, the ID embeds the subject identifier
for human readability:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode">}}\preformatted{DM_0001_01-042    <- row 1 from DM, subject 01-042
ADLB_0047_01-042  <- row 47 from ADLB, subject 01-042
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

For datasets without \code{USUBJID}, a zero-padded sequence is used:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode">}}\preformatted{patients_000001   <- row 1 from the patients dataset
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

This ID persists through \code{\link[=lg_filter]{lg_filter()}}, \code{\link[=lg_derive]{lg_derive()}}, and \code{\link[=lg_join]{lg_join()}},
forming the traceable thread connecting any output row back to its origin.
}

\section{CDISC-specific features}{


Pharmaceutical and clinical users can additionally use:
\itemize{
\item \code{domain} argument in \code{\link[=lg_tag]{lg_tag()}} for CDISC domain codes
(\code{"DM"}, \code{"LB"}, \code{"AE"}, etc.)
\item \code{\link[=lg_population]{lg_population()}} to register SAFFL, ITTFL, PPROTFL flag definitions
\item \code{\link[=lg_spec]{lg_spec()}} to document SDTM-to-ADaM variable derivations
\item \code{\link[=lg_report]{lg_report()}} to generate CDISC Reviewer's Guide-aligned documentation
}

None of these are required for general use.
}

\section{Integration with regulog}{


\code{lineager} and \code{regulog} are complementary packages. Use \code{regulog} to
create a tamper-evident audit trail of the session (who ran what, when,
and why), and \code{lineager} to document the row-level data transformations
within that session. The \code{\link[=lg_report]{lg_report()}} output can be referenced in the
\code{regulog} audit trail via \code{log_action()}.
}

